							<br class="clear"/>
							<!-- End each blog post -->
							
														
							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/erlingkagge/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Erling-Kagge-100x100.jpeg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Erling-Kagge-300x300.jpeg 2x" alt="Erling Kagge" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/erlingkagge/">Erling Kagge</a></h6>
										Norwegian adventurer, philosopher and acclaimed writer Erling Kagge is the first person to complete the “Three poles challenge”—reaching the North Pole, the South Pole, and the summit of Mount Everest on foot. After this record-breaking feat, Kagge attended Cambridge University to study philosophy. He is the author of such beloved books as <em>Silence: In the Age of Noise</em> and <em>Walking: One Step at a Time</em>. He has written for the <em>Financial Times</em>, the <em>New York Times</em>, and <em>The Guardian</em>. He lives in Oslo, Norway.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
